fields.description:
This request is to add a feature to restrict non-admin users from adding GPG commit signature keys / disable visibility of "Add key" button under "Manage account > GPG keys" for non admin users:
{quote}... only allows admins to register a commit signature key, *after verifying the identity associated with the key.*
{quote}

h2. Request
Allow System Administrator users to create projects via the REST API using Personal Access Token (PAT) Auth

h2. Problem report:
Attempting to create a project using the REST API and a PAT in the header as the Auth method fails with "You are not permitted to access this resource"

{panel:title=Example of failing request:|borderStyle=dashed| borderColor=#7383B5 | titleBGColor=#A383B5 | bgColor=#f9ffff}
{code}
curl -i -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -H "Authorization: Bearer Njg2Nzg3NjQ4OTE5OqD2stM90FupJKGtj7K8IkQ7dgRi" -d '{"key": "MTP2", "name": "My Test Project 2", "description": "My Description of my test project 2"}' http://localhost:7990/rest/api/1.0/projects
{code}
{panel}

{panel:title=Full output of error:|borderStyle=dashed| borderColor=#7383B5 | titleBGColor=#A383B5 | bgColor=#f9ffff}
{code}
{"errors":[{"context":null,"message":"You are not permitted to access this resource","exceptionName":"com.atlassian.bitbucket.AuthorisationException"}]}
{code}
{panel}

h2. Workaround:
Currently the REST API works fine with Basic Auth (Username Password) but this is not ideal for automation

h4. Summary

The [Default Reviewers APIs|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-default-reviewers-rest.html] require the internal ids of users being configured as PR default reviewers to be passed for the POST methods.
h5. Default Reviewers POST sample

Here's a sample request payload for a [POST /rest/default-reviewers/1.0/projects/\{projectKey}/condition|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-default-reviewers-rest.html#idp3] request:
{code:javascript}
{
    "sourceMatcher": {
        "active": true,
        "id": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "displayId": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "type": {
            "id": "ANY_REF",
            "name": "Any branch"
        }
    },
    "targetMatcher": {
        "active": true,
        "id": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "displayId": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "type": {
            "id": "ANY_REF",
            "name": "Any branch"
        }
    },
    "reviewers": [
        {
            "name": "user1",
            "emailAddress": "user1@testdomain.com",
            "id": 51,
            "displayName": "User1",
            "active": true,
            "slug": "user1",
            "type": "NORMAL"
        }
    ],
    "requiredApprovals": 1
}
{code}
 - Under "reviewers", the internal id of the user ({{"id": 51}}) is required to be able to find the user and set the user as a default reviewer.

 

The suggestion is to be able to pass an array of usernames instead of requiring the internal ids, similar to what is passed for [Ref Restriction APIs|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-ref-restriction-rest.html].
h5. Ref Restriction POST sample

A sample payload for the [POST /rest/branch-permissions/2.0/projects/\{projectKey}/restrictions|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-ref-restriction-rest.html#idp9] request is:
{code:java}
{
  "type": "pull-request-only",
  "matcher": {
    "id": "refs/heads/hotfix/hotfix2",
    "displayId": "hotfix/hotfix2",
    "type": {
      "id": "BRANCH",
      "name": "Branch"
    },
    "active": "True"
  },
  "users": [
    "admin2",
    "user2"
  ],
  "groups": [],
  "accessKeys": []
}
{code}
 - in this request, an array or user names is passed ({{"users": ["admin2","user2"]}})

h4. Rationale

[Default Reviewers APIs|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-default-reviewers-rest.html] are used for exporting and importing these settings between Bitbucket instances. (Default reviewer settings are currently not included in the entities processed by [Data Center Migration import and export APIs|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver076/data-center-migration-1026535565.html])

Internal ids of users may be different between the source and target instances. It would be more convenient if it was possible to pass usernames instead of first having to find out the correct user ids in the target instance for the default reviewers.

h4. Summary
The source and target matcher fields are different between the GET and POST methods of the [Default Reviewers REST APIs|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-default-reviewers-rest.html]

GET methods use "sourceRefMatcher" and "targetRefMatcher" while POST methods use "sourceMatcher" and "targetMatcher".

Here's a sample response for a [GET /rest/default-reviewers/1.0/projects/\{projectKey\}/conditions|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-default-reviewers-rest.html#idp8] request:
{code:javascript}
[
    {
        "id": 27,
        "scope": {
            "type": "PROJECT",
            "resourceId": 145
        },
        "sourceRefMatcher": {
            "active": true,
            "id": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
            "displayId": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
            "type": {
                "id": "ANY_REF",
                "name": "Any branch"
            }
        },
        "targetRefMatcher": {
            "active": true,
            "id": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
            "displayId": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
            "type": {
                "id": "ANY_REF",
                "name": "Any branch"
            }
        },
        "reviewers": [
            {
                "name": "user1",
                "emailAddress": "user1@testdomain.com",
                "id": 51,
                "displayName": "User1",
                "active": true,
                "slug": "user1",
                "type": "NORMAL",
                "links": {
                    "self": [
                        {
                            "href": "https://bitbucket.myhost.com/users/user1"
                        }
                    ]
                }
            }
        ],
        "requiredApprovals": 1
    }
]
{code}

Here's a sample request payload for a [POST /rest/default-reviewers/1.0/projects/\{projectKey\}/condition|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/7.6.0/bitbucket-default-reviewers-rest.html#idp3] request
{code:javascript}
{
    "sourceMatcher": {
        "active": true,
        "id": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "displayId": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "type": {
            "id": "ANY_REF",
            "name": "Any branch"
        }
    },
    "targetMatcher": {
        "active": true,
        "id": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "displayId": "ANY_REF_MATCHER_ID",
        "type": {
            "id": "ANY_REF",
            "name": "Any branch"
        }
    },
    "reviewers": [
        {
            "name": "user1",
            "emailAddress": "user1@testdomain.com",
            "id": 51,
            "displayName": "User1",
            "active": true,
            "slug": "user1",
            "type": "NORMAL"
        }
    ],
    "requiredApprovals": 1
}
{code}

The difference can cause confusion on the field names to pass in the POST methods, especially since the Default Reviewers REST resources documentation is currently missing examples (this doc issue is tracked in ticket: BSERV-12665)

At the moment, when you open a support ticket for Bitbucket you have to collect multiple zips from multiple servers.

This is both tedious and time consuming when support engineers require multiple and repeated support zips, the longer a ticket is open the more time it takes. Often if the issue is really urgent, it's not something you have capacity to do.

So, instead of creating support zips which you have to download and then upload to the support page, it would be better if the ticket creation and upload was integrated into the existing support pages within Bitbucket server.

At its simplest it could be just a button to the Troubleshooting and Support tools page to transfer the files to transfer.atlassian.com

Alternatively, just provide a shell script which is installed onto the Bitbucket server which does the same thing. I have already written one for my own use:
{code:bash}
#!/bin/bash
 
ZIP_FILE=$1 
TICKET=$2 
 
ZIP="/var/atlassian/application-data/bitbucket/shared/export/$ZIP_FILE" 
 
curl --tlsv1 -u <credentials> -X POST --header "Transfer-Encoding: chunked" -F "files[]=@$ZIP" https://transfer.atlassian.com/api/upload/$TICKET{code}
{{This could be modified so that it generates the zips, picks up the latest files from /var/atlassian/application-data/bitbucket/shared/export and does the upload}}

'path' parameter is not properly filtered in Rest API endpoint {{/rest/api/1.0/projects/\{project_name}/repos/\{repo_name}/commits}}, causing 500 internal server error. This is probably because that 'path' parameter is not properly filtered. The error can be reproduced by either of the following methods: (note in both cases the extra single quote at the end)
 # GET request on: {{BITBUCKET_BASE_URL/rest/api/1.0/projects/\{TEST}/repos/\{test}/commits/test_string'}} or;
 # GET request on: {{BITBUCKET_BASE_URL/rest/api/1.0/projects/\{TEST}/repos/\{test}/commits}}
 with parameters {{\{"path": "test_string'"}}}

Error message:
{code:java}
/usr/bin/git rev-list --format=%H%x02%P%x02%aN%x02%aE%x02%at%x02%cN%x02%cE%x02%ct%n%B%n%x03END%x04 -1 test_string''' exited with code 128 saying: fatal: bad revision 'test_string'''\",\"exceptionName\":\"com.atlassian.bitbucket.scm.CommandFailedException\"
{code}

The new version of the Bitbucket Audit log was introduced with the 7.0 release. 
 Even though the new version provides more verbose information comparing to the old format, one thing is missing there - HTTP session-id (i.e. @32AO0Cx899x57272x0).

Example of the old version of AuthenticationFailureEvent:
{code:java}
172.16.71.1,172.16.71.134 | AuthenticationFailureEvent | - | 1583330349152 | Username for "https | {"authentication-method":"basic","error":"Invalid username or password."} | @32AO0Cx899x57272x0 | -
{code}
Example of the new version of AuthenticationFailureEvent:
{code:java}
{"affectedObjects":[],"auditType":{"action":"User login failed","actionI18nKey":"bitbucket.service.user.audit.action.authenticationfailure","area":"SECURITY","category":"Authentication","categoryI18nKey":"bitbucket.service.audit.category.authentication","level":"BASE"},"author":{"id":"-2","name":"Anonymous","type":"user"},"changedValues":[],"extraAttributes":[{"name":"Error","nameI18nKey":"bitbucket.service.user.audit.attribute.authenticationfailure.error","value":"Invalid username or password."},{"name":"Authentication method","nameI18nKey":"bitbucket.service.user.audit.attribute.authentication.authmethod","value":"form"},{"name":"target","nameI18nKey":"bitbucket.audit.attribute.legacy.target","value":"ie"},{"name":"Load balancer/proxy IP address","nameI18nKey":"atlassian.audit.event.attribute.forwarder","value":"172.16.71.134"}],"method":"Browser","node":"6137e112-c7c1-4d54-a4e3-4b98cccee0fd","source":"172.16.71.1","system":"https://bitbucketdc","timestamp":{"epochSecond":1611659205,"nano":20000000},"version":"1.0"}{code}
Why HTTP session-id is important? It can be used to matching entries from the audit log to the entries of access, application, and profile logs. Also, it helps to troubleshoot on the side of the remote systems using the HAR file or the logs of the client.

h3. Issue Summary

The [GET /rest/api/1.0/projects/PROJECT_KEY/repos/REPO_SLUG/browse|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/6.10.4/bitbucket-rest.html#idp200] API, which is documented to be a [paged API|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/6.10.4/bitbucket-rest.html#paging-params] does not return a {{"nextPageStart"}} attribute when more than one page of response exists (the response contains {{"isLastPage": false}}).
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Commit a file to a repo, with 10 lines, e.g.
{code:java}
line 1
line 2
line 3
line 4
line 5
line 6
line 7
line 8
line 9
line 10
{code}
 # Call the API and pass a "limit=5" parameter, e.g.
{code:java}
curl -u <USER> GET <BITBUCKET_URL>/rest/api/1.0/projects/<PROJECT_KEY>/repos/<REPO_SLUG>/browse/<FILE>?limit=5
{code}
 # Check output:
{code:java}
{
    "lines": [
        {
            "text": "line 1"
        },
        {
            "text": "line 2"
        },
        {
            "text": "line 3"
        },
        {
            "text": "line 4"
        },
        {
            "text": "line 5"
        }
    ],
    "start": 0,
    "size": 5,
    "isLastPage": false
}
{code}
The first 5 lines are returned and {{isLastPage}} attribute is "false". But it does not include a {{nextPageStart}} attribute.

h3. Expected Results

The JSON response will include the {{nextPageStart}} attribute, as documented in the [Paged APIs|https://docs.atlassian.com/bitbucket-server/rest/6.10.4/bitbucket-rest.html#paging-params] section of the REST API documentation.
h3. Actual Results

The {{nextPageStart}} attribute is not included.
h3. Workaround

 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

We have a user-centric endpoint related to repository watchers:
{noformat}
/rest/api/1.0/projects/{projectKey}/repos/{repositorySlug}/watch
{noformat}

It will be useful to add an admin endpoint with a GET method to list all watchers of a repository, in case watches/notification cause issues with the email server and need to be investigated/retrieved by the administrator
